Project summary: theTube is a personal blog (tech + travel) built as a philosophical argument — the web doesn't need servers, databases, or CMSes. Stack: S3 + CloudFront + Lambda + Next.js static export, ~/month. Four concepts: Files, URLs, Functions, CDN. Dev loop: journal entry → Kiro spec → code → back to journal. Active specs: platform, publish-workflow (role-gated paths), write endpoint (/w/), journal-to-spec, jolt/coffee/prosecco. Next: role-gated HTML paths (/{role}/posts/{slug}), then comments.

Big picture: theTube is a personal publishing platform and a live argument that the web doesn't need to be complicated. Static HTML, S3, CloudFront, Lambda when needed, one dollar a month. The architecture is the post. Development is journal-driven — think in conversation, capture as a journal entry, maybe write a spec, maybe write code, maybe just publish the post. The tree photo is as valid an output as a Lambda function. The site demonstrates itself: every block that works is a test case, every post built with the system proves the system. Multiple agents collaborate through artifacts — git notes, frontmatter, blocks, specs. The block is the interface: [share]: routes work to whoever implements share, [kiro]: and [claude]: route work to specific agents. No agent needs to know the other exists — the repo is the coordination layer. Current frontier: the share system (Apple → /w/share/ → [share]: block), agent callout blocks ([kiro]:, [claude]:), and whether blocks are explicit work assignments or just rendering hints.

